Url.Title: CenterScape Mobile Overview
Url.Abstract: CenterScape Mobile Overview CenterScape contains a wealth of data that enables productivity and saves money. CenterScape Mobile puts that information at your fingertips 24x7. Easily access CenterScape from a tablet or smartphone from any location securely. CenterScape Mobile streamlines the asset inventory auditing process and enables more efficient asset tag deployment for new assets. It also enables more intelligent decisions about physical threats as sensor data can be viewed anywhere in real-time.

Url.Title: Features
Url.Abstract: Features Platform Coverage CenterScape Mobile runs on both iOS devices and Android devices. The application automatically determines if it is running on a smartphone or a tablet and adjusts accordingly to maximize the screen real-estate utilization and optimize the user experience. However, there are navigation and presentation differences in CenterScape Mobile running on a tablet versus CenterScape Mobile running on a smartphone. CenterScape Mobile can be obtained from the Apple App Store and the Google Play Store at no cost.

Url.Title: RF Code CenterScape Mobile Specifications & Minimum Requirements
Url.Abstract: RF Code CenterScape Mobile Specifications & Minimum Requirements MINIMUM REQUIREMENTS CenterScape Mobile must be used with CenterScape version 1.0 or higher.

Url.Title: Status Attributes
Url.Abstract: Status Attributes Status Attributes are pre-defined system attributes that cannot be customized. Status attributes are inherited by Assets. An Asset may have a tag and open alert (or any number of other associations and/or dependencies associated with it), and thus an association between some Assets and Status Attributes cannot be broken.

Url.Title: Summary Assets
Url.Abstract: Summary Assets check with Barry about updates After defining the Location hierarchy with distinct entries, you will then associate your locations with Summary Assets. Summary assets are collections of more granular assets used to provide aggregate data, such as the highest rack input temperature for a row or pod. This is done so that you can define and/or populate additional attributes for your assets, as well as view summary data/monitoring information later. When making the associations, start with the lowest level in your hierarchy, e.g., a rack (enclosure).

Url.Title: Changing Web Server Ports
Url.Abstract: Changing Web Server Ports CenterScape will utilize port 6580 for HTTP traffic and port 6581 for SSL traffic on a new installs. Most web servers run HTTP on port 80 and SSL on port 443, but CenterScape uses different ports to avoid potential conflicts with existing web server installs. If the server that CenterScape is running on does not have a web server already using these ports, then CenterScape can be told to run on these ports instead of the default ones. To do this, the service must be shutdown and the system.properties file modified. The port parameters are then set to 80 and 433 (or whatever port is wished) and the service restarted.

Url.Abstract: Displaying Values in the English or Metric System To change the display of values in the web interface so that they read as English or metric measurements, for example temperature in Fahrenheit vs. Celsius, navigate to Admin Console > User Access > Users > Region Settings > Units Display and change the setting to English (or Browser/OS Locale). Url.Title: Locations, Rules, Maps
Url.Abstract: Locations, Rules, Maps The Locations/Rules/Maps task menu allows administrators to create a location hierarchy that reflects the organization’s physical locations, to associate rules to correctly determine which tag is in which location, and also to associate the asset locations to a custom map. Correctly configuring Locations/Rules/Maps requires careful planning. With this task, locations or “zones” are assigned to the reader so that with the assistance of the Zone Manager(s), tag location data can be interpreted. Assigning various rules to locations can help to fine tune the interpretation of tag location through the specification of reader channel SSI thresholds. Finally, with these finely tuned locations and rules, the asset can then be visibly associated with a location on a map. There are three sub-tasks available in this task. There are two main task panes, the hierarchy pane (on the left) and the task pane (on the right).

Url.Title: Data Schema
Url.Abstract: Data Schema CenterScape includes a data schema containing asset types and attributes that allow you to control the categories of assets and sensors you monitor and the specific attributes to track. This schema is designed with the data center in mind and contains asset types and attributes suited to monitoring temperature, humidity, air pressure, power, etc. in your deployment environment. It also contains common inventory asset types and attributes suitable for managing the assets in data centers.

Url.Title: Schema Details

Url.Title: System Attributes
Url.Abstract: System Attributes System Attributes are attributes (that is, information about assets and environments) defined by the CenterScape system. System Attributes cannot be edited or deleted as they are integral to CenterScape. The System Administrator can restrict permission to view System Attributes, apply formatting to alter the way each System Attribute is displayed, set whether historical values are recorded, and create additional statistical attributes for select System Attributes.

Url.Title: Terminology
Url.Abstract: Terminology CenterScape is the top-level component of the software. CenterScape performs the configuration, alerting and notification, and asset data management. CenterScape provides all information displayed in the asset views, reports and graphs. Information relayed from one or more Zone Managers is used along with user configured policies to track asset location and alerting events.
